      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software version control, regression testing suite, and documented release process must be in place and current.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1) is under formal version control with a documented regression test suite covering 47 canonical cases. Release notes and change logs are archived. Achieved level 3 exceeds the MRL 3 required level of 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations through method-of-manufactured-solutions or equivalent benchmark comparisons.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent has been verified against ASME V&V 20 benchmark problems for incompressible viscous flow, including lid-driven cavity and backward-facing step. MMS verification reports are publicly available. Achieved level 3 satisfies the requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) must be quantified for primary QoI (relative hemolysis index) and must be below 5% for all operating points.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted (coarse 4.2 M, medium 11.7 M, fine 31.4 M cells). GCI values for RH index ranged from 0.8% to 1.9% across all five operating conditions, well below the 5% threshold. Richardson extrapolation confirms monotonic convergence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid temperature, hematocrit, anticoagulant protocol, pump speed) must be documented and traceable to the validation dataset.",
      "rationale": "FDA GCBP experimental data were collected under ISO 10993-compliant hemolysis test protocols. Bovine blood at 33±2% hematocrit, 37°C, with heparin anticoagulation. All five flow-speed operating points are documented in the published dataset and replicated in simulation boundary conditions."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (RH index) must be computed for all operating points with uncertainty bounds reported for both experimental and simulation results.",
      "rationale": "RH index computed for all five operating conditions. Simulation RH values fall within experimental uncertainty bands (±15%) at four of five operating points; the fifth point shows 18% deviation, which is within the expanded uncertainty when accounting for blood rheology variability. Normalized RMS error across operating points is 11.3%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (RH index) must be directly relevant to the clinical decision metric and must be the same quantity used in the COU submission.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index is the regulatory-accepted metric for comparative hemolysis assessment per FDA guidance on blood-contacting devices. The same QoI is used in both the validation study and the COU decision. Direct relevance is established without transformation or surrogate mapping."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must address the same class of flow regime, pump geometry, and hemolysis mechanism as the COU device.",
      "rationale": "Validation was performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump, which is the reference geometry for the COU device class. Flow regimes (turbulent, Re 10,000–80,000), rotational speeds (2000–3500 RPM), and hemolysis mechanism (shear-induced RBC damage) are directly representative of CPB operating conditions."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated with residuals below 1e-5 for continuity and momentum equations; round-off error must be assessed as negligible.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to residuals below 1e-6 for continuity and 1e-7 for momentum within 2000 iterations. Double-precision arithmetic used throughout. Round-off error estimated at machine epsilon level, negligible relative to discretization error."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup must be reviewed by an independent analyst; boundary condition and material property inputs must be traceable to documented sources.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup was independently reviewed by a second engineer not involved in the original setup. All boundary conditions and blood property inputs are traceable to published literature and the experimental dataset. No discrepancies were identified during independent review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The turbulence model and hemolysis damage model must be justified for the flow regime and validated against experimental hemolysis data for similar pump geometries.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on published benchmarks for rotating machinery with adverse pressure gradients. Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model calibrated against FDA GCBP experimental data. Model form uncertainty assessed via comparison of three turbulence model variants; SST k-omega showed lowest RMS error against experimental RH index."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sensitivity of RH index to key model inputs (blood viscosity, hemolysis model coefficients, inlet velocity profile) must be quantified via one-way sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "One-way sensitivity analysis conducted for six primary model inputs. Blood viscosity (±10%) produces ±4.2% change in RH index. Hemolysis model exponent (±5%) produces ±8.7% change. Inlet velocity profile shape has less than 1% effect. Total parametric uncertainty budget is consistent with observed validation discrepancy."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental samples must be documented with lot traceability, storage conditions, and preparation protocol consistent with ISO 10993-4.",
      "rationale": "Bovine blood samples used in FDA GCBP validation study are documented with supplier lot numbers, collection dates, storage temperature logs, and preparation protocol per ISO 10993-4. Sample variability across lots assessed via repeated measurements at reference operating point; CV of 6.3% is within acceptable range."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Boundary conditions and material properties used in the simulation must be demonstrated to be equivalent to those present during experimental validation testing.",
      "rationale": "The assessment team concluded that equivalency of input parameters does not apply to this purely computational sensitivity study because no new experimental campaign was conducted alongside the simulation — the validation dataset is historical. Consequently, no formal equivalency assessment was performed. Note: the correct encoding for a factor that genuinely does not apply would be factorStatus 'not-applicable'; the use of 'not-assessed' here means the factor's absence materially weakens credibility at MRL 3, constituting weakness W-EP-04."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-mrl3-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen credibility factors are assessed and meet or exceed required levels at MRL 3. The equivalency of input parameters factor is recorded as not-assessed on the basis that the validation dataset is historical and no concurrent experimental campaign was conducted. The team judged this acceptable given the high quality of the FDA GCBP reference dataset; however, this judgment is not supported by a formal equivalency demonstration, and the factor's not-assessed status at MRL 3 constitutes an unresolved epistemic gap (W-EP-04). Decision accepted pending regulatory review of this gap.",
